d by the early 1900s. He emphasizes the role of the emerging dealer/gallery market and of modernist art historiographies in evaluating modern art and legitimizing it through the formation of a canon of modernist masters. In describing the canon-building of modern dealerships, Jensen considers the new "ideological dealer" and explores the commercial construction of artistic identity through such rhetorical concepts as temperament and "independent art" and through such institutional structures as the retrospective. His inquiries into the fate of the juste milieu, a group of dissidents who saw themselves as "true heirs" of Impressionism, and his look at a new form of art history emerging in Germany further expose a linear, dealer- oriented history of modernist art constructed by or through the modernists themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt criticismzEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aArt criticismzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aArtzEuropexMarketingxHistoryy19th century. 0aArtzEuropexMarketingxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt, Moderny19th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aModernism (Art)zEurope. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aAcademic art.  aAesthetic Theory.  aAestheticism.  aAlfred Rethel.  aAlfred Sisley.  aAmbroise Vollard.  aArt Nouveau.  aArt criticism.  aArt for art's sake.  aArt museum.  aArts and Crafts movement.  aAuguste Rodin.  aAvant-garde.  aBarbizon school.  aBerlin Secession.  aBerthe Weill.  aCamille Pissarro.  aCentral Europe.  aChampfleury.  aClass action.  aClassicism.  aContemporary art.  aDaniel-Henry Kahnweiler.  aDecadent movement.  aDer Blaue Reiter.  aDescriptive Catalogue (1809).  aDreyfus affair.  aEdvard Munch.  aFrantz Jourdain.  aFrench art.  aGeorges Seurat.  aGeorges de La Tour.  a